---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ConceptPageHero from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPageHero.astro';
import ConceptPager from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPager.astro';
import { getConcept } from '../../lib/concepts';

const c = getConcept('relativity');
---

<Layout title={`${c.title} | Identity Engineering`}>
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<ConceptPageHero
			scene={c.scene}
			tag={`${c.tag} · ${c.layerLabel}`}
			title={c.title}
			lede={c.blurb}
			scrollHint={c.scrollHint}
		/>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Interactive layer</div>
				<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white md:text-4xl">
					Identity is not absolute — and neither is Spannung.
				</h2>
				<p>
					<strong class="text-white/80">Relativity</strong> states that identity exists only in relation to another observing identity. This is the bridge from single-identity geometry to the interactive field.
				</p>
				<p>
					The same holds for <strong class="text-white/80">Spannung</strong>: tension does not exist in isolation. It arises in relation — between past and future, between internal drives and external demands, between one identity and another. Since identity itself only becomes real through observation and relation, Spannung is not an optional add-on. It is constitutive of identity.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02] px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<div class="mb-6 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Implications</div>
				<ul class="space-y-6 text-lg text-white/55">
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Observer-dependence:</strong> how our stem is read depends on the other’s frame (their mass, curvature, vision). The tension we experience is always co-shaped by how we are observed and how we observe others.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Mutual definition:</strong> relationships co-produce both identity geometry and the tension fields between stems. Isolation is an idealization, not the default ontology.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">No tension-free identity:</strong> Because identity requires relation to be recognized and maintained, and because Spannung arises in relation, there is no such thing as a tension-free identity. The question is never whether tension exists, but what quality, intensity, and direction it has.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">AI-era stress test:</strong> when copies are cheap, the question “same as whom, for whom, under what observation?” becomes central — and with it the question of which tensions are being preserved or erased in the act of observation.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<p>
					<strong class="text-white/80">Engineering work:</strong> Design for legible differentials under observation. Make the State Differential transparent enough that another identity (human or artificial) can track sameness-as-trajectory without freezing us into a copyable snapshot. At the same time, become aware that every act of observation and relation co-creates the tension field in which identity is maintained.
				</p>
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-black/30 p-6">
					<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[3px] text-white/40 mb-3">Practical probes</div>
					<ul class="space-y-3 text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
						<li>Which observer groups matter most for my continuity claims, and what tension does their observation create?</li>
						<li>What evidence do they need to track real continuity without flattening the tension that makes my trajectory meaningful?</li>
						<li>Where am I still over-relying on static, copyable signals that hide the relational and tensional nature of my identity?</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ConceptPager id="relativity" />
	</main>
</Layout>
